HOTEL BOOKING CANCELLATION ANALYSIS AND PREDICTIVE MODELING REPORT

1. Introduction
This report presents a comprehensive analysis of historical hotel booking data from a global hotel chain. The primary goal is to minimize revenue leakage by identifying key drivers of Average Daily Rate (ADR) and building a robust predictive model for booking cancellation risk.
Objectives
•	Hypothesis Testing: Validate differences in ADR across hotel types and assess the association between deposit requirements and cancellation risk.
•	Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA): Identify key booking and customer characteristics (e.g., lead time, customer type) associated with cancellations.
•	Predictive Modeling: Develop a Logistic Regression Model to forecast the probability of a booking being canceled, enabling proactive interventions.

2. Dataset Overview
The dataset includes over 113,000 clean hotel bookings after preprocessing.
Key Variables
Variable	Description	Type
is_canceled	Booking canceled (Yes/No)	Factor (Response)
adr	Average Daily Rate (revenue per night)	Numeric
lead_time	Days between booking date and arrival date	Numeric
deposit_type	Type of deposit (No Deposit, Non Refund, Refundable)	Factor
hotel	Hotel category (City or Resort)	Factor
total_of_special_requests	Customer engagement metric	Numeric


Data Cleaning and Metrics
•	Missing values for children were imputed as 0.
•	Bookings with ADR ≤ 0 or extreme outliers were removed to ensure statistical integrity.
•	Overall cancellation mix: ~37.5% canceled vs. ~62.5% fulfilled.
3. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
3.1 Lead Time Distribution
•	Canceled bookings have a significantly longer planning horizon than fulfilled bookings.
•	Median Lead Times:
o	Canceled: ~115 days
o	Not Canceled: ~47 days
•	Interpretation: Bookings made far in advance are more likely to cancel, suggesting early-bookers have flexible plans or face schedule/price changes.


3.2 ADR Distribution Across Hotel Types
•	City Hotels: Higher median ADR (~€105) and greater price variability
•	Resort Hotels: More stable ADR (~€86) distribution


3.3 Total Stay Distribution 
•	Mean total stay:
o	Canceled: 3.45 nights
o	Not Canceled: 3.42 nights
o	Total stay duration is almost identical for canceled vs. non-canceled bookings
o	The distributions overlap almost perfectly, indicating no meaningful relationship between stay length and cancellation behavior.
o	Interpretation
o	Guests do not appear to cancel more or less based on how long they intended to stay.
o	This suggests that stay length reflects trip type, not commitment level.
•	Interpretation: Stay length is not a significant predictor of cancellations; it reflects trip type rather than commitment


3.4 Customer Type vs Cancellation
•	Cancellation rates:
o	Transient: ~41%
o	Contract: ~26%
o	Group: ~7%
•	Interpretation: Transient guests are the most volatile; group bookings show the lowest cancellation risk.


3.5 Deposit Type vs Cancellation
•	Cancellation rates:
o	No Deposit: ~28%
o	Refundable: ~21%
o	Non Refund: ~99%
•	Chi-Square Test: χ² = 27,335, p < 2.2e-16 → extremely strong association
•	Interpretation: Deposit policies strongly influence guest behavior; Non Refund category shows unusual skew, likely due to data reporting rules.


3.6 Hotel Type vs Cancellation
•	Cancellation rates:
o	City Hotels: ~42%
o	Resort Hotels: ~27%
•	Interpretation: City hotels attract short-notice business travelers → higher cancellations.
•	Operational Implication: Different overbooking strategies may be needed for city vs. resort properties.


4. Hypothesis Testing
4.1 Difference in Mean ADR by Hotel Type
•	Null Hypothesis (H₀): Mean ADR is the same for City and Resort hotels
•	Descriptive Statistics:
o	City Hotels: Mean ADR ≈ 105.41, SD ≈ 33.30
o	Resort Hotels: Mean ADR ≈ 86.43, SD ≈ 46.50
•	ANOVA Result: F ≈ 5756, p < 2e-16 → reject H₀
•	Interpretation: City Hotels charge ~€19 more on average
•	Robustness Check: Levene’s test indicates unequal variances; Welch’s t-test confirms significance

 
4.2 Association Between Cancellation and Deposit Type
•	Null Hypothesis (H₀): Deposit type and cancellation status are independent
•	Result: Chi-square statistic ≈ 27,335, p < 2.2e-16 → reject H₀
•	Interpretation: Deposit rules significantly impact cancellations; Non Refund deposits behave unusually


5. Predictive Modeling: Logistic Regression
5.1 Model Summary
•	Dependent Variable: is_canceled (Yes/No)
•	Key Predictors: Lead Time, ADR, Deposit Type, Hotel Type, Customer Type, Total Special Requests
•	Model Fit: Null deviance = 105,194; Residual deviance = 71,954; AIC = 72,012
•	Multicollinearity: VIF < 3 for all variables

Model Logic:
•	Early-bookers and high-price bookings more fragile
•	Loyal guests & engaged guests rarely cancel
•	Non-Refund coded bookings behave uniquely
•	Transient guests most volatile segment


5.2 Key Predictors and Interpretation (Odds Ratios)
