Model Insight: Conservative classifier prioritizes precision and specificity, minimizing false alarms.

7. Key Business Insights
Finding	Implication
City Hotels have higher ADR and higher cancellation risk (~42%)	City Hotels serve more business and short-notice travelers; higher pricing requires tighter risk management and dynamic pricing adjustments.
Customer Engagement (Special Requests)	Bookings with more special requests are significantly less likely to cancel (Odds Ratio ~0.49). Engagement signals commitment—hotels can proactively reach out to these guests for upselling or loyalty programs.
Lead Time is the strongest continuous predictor	Bookings made >100 days in advance have the highest cancellation probability. Early confirmation reminders or deposit incentives could reduce cancellations.
Transient guests and online travel agency (OTA) bookings	These segments show 2–3x higher cancellation odds compared to group or contract bookings. Targeted deposit rules or prepayment can mitigate risk.
Non Refund deposits show extreme skew (~99% cancellation)	Indicates a potential data artifact or business rule; immediate data audit is necessary to correct reporting and prevent model bias.

Additional Operational Insights
•	Overbooking strategies should differ by hotel type: higher buffer for City Hotels, moderate for Resorts.
•	ADR variability is higher in City Hotels, reflecting business traveler behavior and flexible pricing opportunities.
•	Early-bird bookings with refundable deposits represent the highest risk class—these should be actively monitored.
•	Special requests and prior booking history can be used to create a risk-scoring system for proactive management.


8. Recommendations
•	High-Risk Booking Management: Flag bookings with long lead times or prior cancellations; use reminders or incentives to convert to non-refundable deposits.
•	Hotel Type Strategy: Maintain higher ADR at City Hotels, but implement stricter deposits or shorter free cancellation windows to reduce risk.
•	Customer Engagement: Encourage early special requests and reward repeat guests through loyalty programs to lower cancellation likelihood.
•	Deposit Policy Optimization: Introduce partial or tiered deposits for early bookings to discourage speculative reservations.
•	Target High-Risk Segments: Focus on transient travelers and OTA bookings with prepayment or personalized communication.
•	Operational Monitoring: Use dashboards to track lead time, deposit type, ADR, customer type, and engagement metrics for proactive interventions.
•	Data Integrity: Audit Non Refund deposit data to ensure model accuracy and reliable decision-making.


9. Conclusion 
The analysis of over 113,000 hotel bookings demonstrates that cancellation behavior is strongly influenced by deposit type, lead time, hotel category, customer type, and engagement metrics.
Key Takeaways:
1.	Deposit Type is the most powerful categorical predictor; Non Refund data needs immediate review.
2.	Lead Time drives early cancellation risk—long-horizon bookings (>100 days) are most vulnerable.
3.	Hotel Type differentiates risk profiles: City Hotels have higher cancellation rates and price variability; Resort Hotels show more stability.
4.	Customer Segments: Transient and OTA guests are high-risk; repeat and engaged guests are protective.
5.	Price Influence: Higher ADR bookings show slightly increased cancellation propensity; pricing strategies should balance revenue and risk.
6.	Engagement Signals: Special requests and prior booking history are strong protective factors; operational focus on engagement can improve retention.
Operational Recommendations:
•	Implement risk-based overbooking strategies according to hotel type and booking profile.
•	Optimize deposit policies with partial/tiered deposits for early bookings.
•	Use engagement-driven interventions (special requests, reminders, loyalty perks) to reduce cancellations.
•	Establish a real-time monitoring dashboard for predictive cancellation risk, enabling proactive operational decisions.
Strategic Impact:
•	The Logistic Regression model (AUC ≈ 0.83) is robust, generalizes well to unseen bookings, and allows hotels to forecast cancellations with high confidence.
•	Effective implementation of these strategies can enhance revenue protection, optimize operational efficiency, and reduce uncertainty in room inventory management.
•	Immediate data audit for Non Refund deposits is critical for maintaining predictive accuracy and operational reliability.
